df = pd.read_csv("data.csv", encoding="latin-1")
df_raw = df.copy()   # Keep a backup for comparison later
df['InvoiceDate'] = pd.to_datetime(df['InvoiceDate'], errors='coerce')
df['IsReturn'] = df['InvoiceNo'].astype(str).str.startswith('C')
df = df[~((df['Quantity'] <= 0) & (df['IsReturn'] == False))]
df = df[df['UnitPrice'] > 0]  # Unit price cannot be zero or negative
df['TotalPrice'] = df['Quantity'] * df['UnitPrice']
df['Country'] = df['Country'].astype(str).str.upper().str.strip()
df['CustomerID'] = df['CustomerID'].astype('Int64')
df = df.drop_duplicates()
df = df.dropna(subset=['InvoiceDate', 'StockCode', 'Description', 'Quantity', 'UnitPrice'])

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# ---------------- Global Style ----------------
sns.set_theme(style="whitegrid", context="notebook")
plt.rcParams["figure.dpi"] = 110   # crisper without being huge

# =========================================
# 0. PREP
# =========================================
df["InvoiceDate"] = pd.to_datetime(df["InvoiceDate"], errors="coerce")
df["TotalPrice"] = df["Quantity"] * df["UnitPrice"]
df["DayName"] = df["InvoiceDate"].dt.day_name()
df["Hour"] = df["InvoiceDate"].dt.hour
df["Month"] = df["InvoiceDate"].dt.to_period("M")

# nice palette to reuse
palette_main = sns.color_palette("Set2")
palette_alt = sns.color_palette("crest")


# =====================================================
# 1) DATA OVERVIEW  Monthly order count
# =====================================================
monthly_orders = df.groupby("Month")["InvoiceNo"].nunique().reset_index()
monthly_orders["Month"] = monthly_orders["Month"].astype(str)

plt.figure(figsize=(6,4))
sns.barplot(data=monthly_orders, x="Month", y="InvoiceNo", palette=palette_main)
plt.title("Monthly Distribution of Unique Invoices")
plt.xlabel("Month")
plt.ylabel("Number of Invoices")
plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha="right")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()


# =====================================================
# 2) CUSTOMER ANALYSIS  Orders per customer
# =====================================================
cust_orders = (
    df.dropna(subset=["CustomerID"])
      .groupby("CustomerID")["InvoiceNo"]
      .nunique()
)

plt.figure(figsize=(6,4))
sns.histplot(cust_orders, bins=30, kde=False, color=palette_main[0])
plt.title("Distribution of Customer Purchase Frequency")
plt.xlabel("Number of Orders per Customer")
plt.ylabel("Number of Customers")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Top 10 customers by order count
top10_cust = cust_orders.sort_values(ascending=False).head(10).reset_index()
top10_cust["CustomerID"] = top10_cust["CustomerID"].astype(str)

plt.figure(figsize=(6,4))
sns.barplot(data=top10_cust, x="CustomerID", y="InvoiceNo", palette=palette_alt)
plt.title("Top 10 Most Active Customers by Number of Orders")
plt.xlabel("Customer ID")
plt.ylabel("Number of Orders")
plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha="right")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()


# =====================================================
# 3) PRODUCT ANALYSIS  Top products & revenue
# =====================================================
top10_products_qty = (
    df.groupby("Description")["Quantity"]
      .sum()
      .sort_values(ascending=False)
      .head(10)
      .reset_index()
)

plt.figure(figsize=(9,6))
sns.barplot(data=top10_products_qty, x="Description", y="Quantity",
            palette=palette_main)
plt.title("Top 10 Most Purchased Products (By Quantity Sold)")
plt.xlabel("Product Description")
plt.ylabel("Total Quantity Sold")
plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha="right")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

top10_products_rev = (
    df.groupby("Description")["TotalPrice"]
      .sum()
      .sort_values(ascending=False)
      .head(10)
      .reset_index()
)

plt.figure(figsize=(9,6))
sns.barplot(data=top10_products_rev, x="Description", y="TotalPrice",
            palette="flare")
plt.title("Top 10 Highest Revenue-Generating Products")

plt.ylabel("Total Revenue ()")
plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha="right")

# Recency reference date (1 day after last purchase)
reference_date = df['InvoiceDate'].max() + dt.timedelta(days=1)

# Calculate RFM metrics
RFM = df.groupby('CustomerID').agg({
    'InvoiceDate': lambda x: (reference_date - x.max()).days,  # Recency
    'InvoiceNo': 'nunique',                                   # Frequency
    'TotalPrice': 'sum'                                       # Monetary
})

RFM.rename(columns={
    'InvoiceDate': 'Recency',
    'InvoiceNo': 'Frequency',
    'TotalPrice': 'Monetary'
}, inplace=True)

5. RFM SCORING USING QUARTILES (1 = low, 4 = high)

In[6]:
# --- Recency Quartiles (fine) ---
RFM['R_rank'] = pd.qcut(RFM['Recency'], 4, labels=[4,3,2,1], duplicates='drop')

# --- Frequency: Skewed  use custom bins ---
max_f = RFM['Frequency'].max()

RFM['F_rank'] = pd.cut(
    RFM['Frequency'],
    bins=[0, 1, 2, 4, max_f],
    labels=[1, 2, 3, 4],
    include_lowest=True
)

# --- Monetary Quartiles ---
RFM['M_rank'] = pd.qcut(RFM['Monetary'], 4, labels=[1,2,3,4], duplicates='drop')

# --- Combine scores ---
RFM['RFM_Score'] = (
    RFM['R_rank'].astype(str) +
    RFM['F_rank'].astype(str) +
    RFM['M_rank'].astype(str)
)

6. K-MEANS CLUSTERING ON STANDARDIZED RFM VALUES

In[18]:
X = RFM[['Recency', 'Frequency', 'Monetary']]

scaler = StandardScaler()
X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)

# Try different K values (optional elbow plot)
k_range = range(2, 10)
sse = []
for k in k_range:
    km = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=42)
    km.fit(X_scaled)
    sse.append(km.inertia_)

sns.set(style="whitegrid")

plt.figure(figsize=(7, 6))  # <-- reduced size
plt.plot(range(2, 10), sse, marker='o', linestyle='-', linewidth=2, markersize=6)
plt.title("Elbow Method for Optimal Clusters", fontsize=12)
plt.xlabel("K (Clusters)", fontsize=11)
plt.ylabel("SSE", fontsize=11)
plt.xticks(range(2, 10), fontsize=10)
plt.yticks(fontsize=10)
plt.axvline(x=4, color='red', linestyle='--', linewidth=1)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Choose K=4 (common in RFM segmentation)
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=4, random_state=42)
RFM['Cluster'] = kmeans.fit_predict(X_scaled)
